Changes to a production vehicle from one model year to the next are often marginal, if not nonexistent. But with a performance model like the Porsche 911 GT3, you can't get away with not pushing further alongside your competition. And as 2016 rolled over to 2017, the GT3 saw one of its biggest changes in years. The famous flat-six that powers the driver's 911 was bumped up to a nice, round, 4.0-liter displacement. That resulted in an even 500-horsepower output, matching the outgoing GT3 RS and trending the more affordable GT3 model even further up the ladder. New shocks, rubber, and rear-wheel steering are among the smaller changes that add up to the 991.2 GT3's all-around prowess on road and track. Changes to a production vehicle from one model year to the next are often marginal, if not nonexistent. But with a performance model like the Porsche 911 GT3, you can't get away with not pushing further alongside your competition. And as 2016 rolled over to 2017, the GT3 saw one of its biggest changes in years. The famous flat-six that powers the driver's 911 was bumped up to a nice, round, 4.0-liter displacement. That resulted in an even 500-horsepower output, matching the outgoing GT3 RS and trending the more affordable GT3 model even further up the ladder. New shocks, rubber, and rear-wheel steering are among the smaller changes that add up to the 991.2 GT3's all-around prowess on road and track. The tapering roofline has been lowered, exposing fewer surfaces to the air. The front track has been widened for improved cornering stability. Circling around to the side of the 911, one can see that the exterior mirrors are now mounted directly on the doors resulting in improved aerodynamics as well as a longer wheelbase, and shorter overhangs at both front and rear. The new engines follow the time honored 911 design: six horizontally opposed cylinders providing a lower center of gravity. Output has been increased to 350hp in the 911 Carrera , 400hp in the 911 Carrera S, 475hp in the 911 GT3, 520hp in the 911 Turbo, and 560hp in the 911 Turbo S. This power is transmitted by the introduction of a 7-speed manual gearbox or, optionally, the Porsche Doppelkupplung transmission, which offers gear changes with virtually no interruption in the flow of power. The refined steering wheel features a high-grip smooth-leather rim. Fitted as standard, the 911 has refined sport seats that combine comfort with racing-style support and now feature 4-way power adjustment. The traditional choice of interior options includes innovative additions. Beautiful 2016 Porsche Boxster Spyder shown in White over black leather and alcantara interior. Porsche revealed the latest Spyder model in April 2015 at the New York Auto Show. The styling of the car is similar to the previous generation Spyder, continuing the twin hump rear deck and manually operated canvas top. It also shares some styling with the Cayman GT4, using the same front and rear fascia. The engine is also shared with the Cayman GT4, a 3.8L flat-6, making this the largest capacity and most powerful engine used in a Boxster with 385 bhp. It is also the lightest current Porsche, weighing 2,899 lb. This was achieved through the use of aluminum doors and rear lid, the manually operated roof and unique light weight 20 inch wheels. The air conditioning and audio system are also removed, although can be added as no cost options. Braking is via larger brakes than used on the Boxster S, being 340mm front and 330mm rear units taken from the 911 Carrera S. It also shares from the GT4 a limited slip differential combined with Porsche Torque Vectoring and features a 30mm lower ride height. Additionally it also borrows the steering rack from the 911 Turbo S along with the same reduced diameter GT steering wheel as used in both the GT3 and GT4. The only gearbox available is a 6 speed manual. The Spyder was only available as a 2016 model with a total worldwide production of 2400 units. This lovely example Boxster Spyder is fitted with the following options, 64L fuel tank, white exterior paint, wheel center caps with colored crest, door opening loops in color of decorative stitch, fire extinguisher, supplemental safety bars in exterior color, wind deflector, air conditioning, leather with alcantara in conjunction with stitching in contrasting yellow color, mobile phone integration, Porsche dynamic lights system (PDLS), light design package, stitching in contrasting color, reverse camera, steering wheel trim and gear lever in smooth finish leather in black, rear side air>

The all-new 2017 Porsche Panamera A genuine sports car with the comfort of a luxury sedan, without any compromises in everyday life. A more striking front end, sharper lateral lines as well as rearward tapering roof and rear window surfaces underline the sports car characteristics of the Panamera. What is particularly striking is the new, characteristic light panel at the noticeably broader rear. There are 3 engines to choose from including a 2.9L turbo V6 or a 3.0L turbo V6 which both make 330hp as well as a 2.9L twin-turbo V6 which makes 440hp and is good for a 0-60 as low as 4.0 sec w/ Sport Chrono. Power is transmitted via the newly developed 8-speed Porsche Doppelkupplung with Auto Start Stop function. The base Panamera comes standard with RWD but all other trims come standard with Porsche Traction Management active all-wheel drive. The Sport Chrono package allows you to choose between 4 driving modes including Normal, SPORT, SPORT PLUS, and Individual. The front seats offer a high level of comfort and provide support in fast corners without restricting freedom of movement. Available as an option, adaptive sport seats (18-way, electric) including memory package provide even better lateral support. The rear features two separate seats with plenty of leg and headroom and offering excellent lateral support through fast corners without sacrificing comfort. On request, the power seats are also available with a massage function, front and rear. The new Porsche Communication Management is your central control unit for audio, navigation and communication. The new generation with online navigation, cell-phone preparation, audio interfaces and voice operation has a high-resolution 12-inch touchscreen display.

1988 Porsche 911 Turbo "Slant Nose" convertible with only 3250 miles from new!!  Original, numbers matching 505-code car as confirmed by Porsche Certificate of Authenticity.  It is a two-owner, California car ready to compliment any fine collection.     After a six-year hiatus because of new US emissions regulations and the development of a new electronic engine management system to control exhaust emissions, Porsche brought the 911 Turbo back to the U.S. market in 1986.  During that period, clients asked the factory to create a street-legal version of the brilliant 935 Group 5 car under its Special Wishes Program Sonderwunschprogramm.  The highly coveted edition featured a flat, aerodynamic nose with retractable headlights, widened and louvered front fenders, more muscular rear quarters with air intakes and stylish strakes, extended and boxed rocker panels, an additional oil cooler, and a large rear spoiler, which housed an intercooler atop the engine lid.  After 930s returned to the U.S. market in 1986, Porsche formalized the design the following year, with option number 505, also known as the 930S.  Equipped with a four-speed manual transmission and limited-slip differential, this stunning Guards Red 1988 930 has only 3,250 miles and represents a rarity even for this limited edition collectible model.  2 keys, books, and records included.  Quite possibly the finest example currently offered for sale.  Offers welcomed and trades considered.  Worldwide delivery available.  Please call or email for more information.
